and you hear the click.

19:06.078 --> 19:07.413
(MIMICS CLICKING)

19:07.513 --> 19:09.148
And then free fall.

19:09.248 --> 19:11.183
(WAILING)

19:11.283 --> 19:14.123
And he hit. And I was like, "Whoa!"

19:16.589 --> 19:18.324
And at that moment,
they call me in, you know.

19:18.424 --> 19:20.493
(IN FEMALE VOICE) "Mr. Iglesias."
(IN NORMAL VOICE) "Hey, wish me luck."

19:20.593 --> 19:22.033
(SPEAKING INCOHERENTLY)

19:22.294 --> 19:25.164
So I walk into the office.
I'm greeted by a nurse.

19:25.264 --> 19:26.666
The nurse is really nice.

19:26.766 --> 19:29.669
In addition to being nice,
she's actually a fan,

19:29.769 --> 19:31.504
which made it so much better for me.

19:31.604 --> 19:33.005
She comes over, and she's like,

19:33.105 --> 19:35.841
"Mr. Iglesias, this is such an honor.

19:35.941 --> 19:38.044
"I'm such a huge fan.

19:38.144 --> 19:41.723
"I am going to make this
as painless as possible.

19:42.448 --> 19:44.491
"I have to weigh you."

19:45.451 --> 19:47.853
I'm like, "You know what? I'm good.
I weighed myself at the house.

19:47.953 --> 19:50.895
"I'm 445 pounds. I'm good."

19:51.323 --> 19:53.525
"I have to confirm that."

19:53.793 --> 19:57.338
And in my head, I'm like,
"Why would I make that up?"

19:58.464 --> 20:00.733
You know what I mean?
Like, if you're 200 pounds

20:00.833 --> 20:04.036
and you lie and say
you're 195, I get it,

20:04.136 --> 20:06.405
but once you achieve
a certain level of...

20:06.505 --> 20:08.685
(WAILING)

20:08.974 --> 20:10.619
It's pretty clear.

20:11.544 --> 20:13.212
So I said, "Fine. Where's it at?"

20:13.312 --> 20:15.214
"Excuse me?" "Where's it at?
Where's the scale?"

20:15.314 --> 20:16.983
Because I want to
walk up to the scale,

20:17.083 --> 20:18.718
so I can grab the stupid brick,

20:18.818 --> 20:21.554
pick it up, slide it all the way
to the end, and put it down.

20:21.654 --> 20:23.322
You know the scale I'm
talking about, right?

20:23.422 --> 20:25.257
The one that has that heavy arm,
where you get on,

20:25.357 --> 20:27.036
and it's loud? (THUDS)

20:28.260 --> 20:29.729
I call it the "Scale Nazi."

20:29.829 --> 20:32.098
You get on, and
it's like, "Sieg Heil!"

20:32.198 --> 20:33.706
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

20:34.567 --> 20:35.871
Mmm-hmm.

20:37.703 --> 20:38.904
She starts laughing.

20:39.004 --> 20:41.674
She goes, "Mr. Iglesias,
you are so silly.

20:41.774 --> 20:44.614
"Actually, our scale is industrial."

20:48.347 --> 20:51.017
Any time someone uses
the word "industrial"

20:51.117 --> 20:54.127
and you're in the sentence,
ho-ho, you messed up.

20:55.588 --> 20:58.491
She goes, "Mr. Iglesias,
it's built directly into the floor.

20:58.591 --> 20:59.992
"Stand on the little X."

21:00.092 --> 21:03.068
I'm like, "Oh, my God! I'm a semi."

21:06.031 --> 21:07.366
And then she gives me instructions.

21:07.466 --> 21:09.969
She goes, "Yeah, Mr. Iglesias,
listen. Stand still.

21:10.069 --> 21:11.837
"I'm going to press the
little button on the wall.

21:11.937 --> 21:13.172
"It's going to make a sound,

21:13.272 --> 21:16.008
"and then your weight is going
to appear in the little window."

21:16.108 --> 21:17.510
And I'm like, "Make a sound?"

21:17.610 --> 21:20.586
In my head, I'm like,
"I hope it's not, you know..."

21:20.713 --> 21:22.620
(MIMICS HONKING)

21:23.449 --> 21:24.817
So I'm bracing myself. I'm waiting.

21:24.917 --> 21:28.287
I'm like... (GRUNTING) And as she
presses it and it was actually cute.

21:28.387 --> 21:30.191
It was like a casino sound.
It was like... (BEEPS)

21:30.556 --> 21:31.624
(TRILLS)

21:31.724 --> 21:32.825
(PINGS)

21:32.925 --> 21:34.326
"Hold on! My shoes!"

21:34.426 --> 21:35.866
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

21:36.095 --> 21:38.631
(CHUCKLES) You're laughing.
It's three pounds, bro.

21:38.731 --> 21:40.433
(ALL LAUGHING)

21:41.100 --> 21:44.136
So then she walks me
into the doctor's office.

21:44.236 --> 21:45.638
I sit down. Doctor walks in,

21:45.738 --> 21:47.139
and we spoke for an hour.

21:47.239 --> 21:50.076
In a nutshell, what he says is
that he wants to take my stomach,

21:50.176 --> 21:53.479
which, in his opinion, is the
size of an NFL football,

21:53.579 --> 21:56.816
and he wants to cut it and make
it the size of a hard-boiled egg.

21:56.916 --> 21:58.884
Therefore, you only eat this much,

21:58.984 --> 22:00.820
and you lose weight with time.

22:00.920 --> 22:02.655
Problem with gastric bypass is that

22:02.755 --> 22:05.991
if you don't stick to their
program religiously,

22:06.091 --> 22:07.660
not only will you not lose weight,

22:07.760 --> 22:09.228
you will gain weight,

22:09.328 --> 22:11.163
and you'll have a series
of complications.

22:11.263 --> 22:13.566
And then he asked,
"Do you travel a lot?"

22:13.666 --> 22:16.235
I'm like, "I'm on the road
46 weeks out of the year."

22:16.335 --> 22:17.703
He goes, "This is not
going to work for you."

22:17.803 --> 22:19.983
I'm like, "I agree. I like two eggs."

22:20.206 --> 22:21.885
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

22:22.341 --> 22:23.409
I said, "Well, what should I do?"

22:23.509 --> 22:25.244
He goes, "I don't know,
but this isn't going to work."

22:25.344 --> 22:27.513
So I left the office.
I was bummed out, you guys.

22:27.613 --> 22:28.681
I get in my car.

22:28.781 --> 22:30.182
I was so depressed, because I'm like,

22:30.282 --> 22:31.751
"Someone told me I
got two years to live.

22:31.851 --> 22:35.187
"Surgery is my last hope."
And so I started crying.

22:35.287 --> 22:36.722
I was sad. I was in
the car. I'm crying.

22:36.822 --> 22:38.357
I'm like, "What the
hell am I going to do?"

22:38.457 --> 22:42.161
And the only thing that could
cheer me up was a drive-through.

22:43.162 --> 22:44.363
And I know that sounds crazy.

22:44.463 --> 22:46.365
Some of you are like,
"Isn't that what got you

22:46.465 --> 22:48.300
"in that position to begin with?"

22:48.400 --> 22:50.970
Yes! But it's the only
thing that made sense.

22:51.070 --> 22:52.805
There's a reason why it's called

22:52.905 --> 22:55.207
"comfort food." Think about that.

22:55.307 --> 22:57.143
Any time you see someone
eating a burger,

22:57.243 --> 23:00.014
they never look sad.
They always look happy.

23:00.479 --> 23:02.047
You might look sad walking in,

23:02.147 --> 23:03.449
you might look sad walking out,

23:03.549 --> 23:06.485
but when the actual event of
eating a burger is happening,

23:06.585 --> 23:08.765
life couldn't be better.

23:08.988 --> 23:10.422
That's right.

23:10.522 --> 23:11.723
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

23:14.360 --> 23:17.496
My girl told me that I make
sounds when I eat burgers.

23:17.596 --> 23:19.465
I didn't know. Apparently I do.

23:19.565 --> 23:21.400
I'm eating a burger, and I'm like...

23:21.500 --> 23:22.974
(MOANING)

23:28.274 --> 23:31.644
She was like, "Are you eating that,
or are you eating that?"

23:31.744 --> 23:34.151
(MOUTHING)

23:36.048 --> 23:38.918
Think about it. Who's sad when
they're eating fast food?

23:39.018 --> 23:39.952
I'll tell you who's sad,

23:40.052 --> 23:42.588
the person eating a salad,
watching someone eat fast food.

23:42.688 --> 23:45.090
That's who's sad. You know?

23:45.190 --> 23:49.270
So I pull up to this fast-food
restaurant with a big "M" on it.

23:50.129 --> 23:52.431
And the guy on the speaker's like,
you know, "May I help you?"

23:52.531 --> 23:55.769
And I'm crying. I'm like,
"You have no idea."

23:56.769 --> 24:01.307
What I eventually wound up doing,
you guys, is I started low-carbing.

24:01.407 --> 24:04.343
Now, I am not eating
healthy by no means, okay?

24:04.443 --> 24:08.314
I still eat fast food every single day,
and people question it.

24:08.414 --> 24:11.483
"How do you eat fast food
and lose 100 pounds?"

24:11.583 --> 24:13.118
I'll give you an example.

24:13.218 --> 24:15.888
I'll go to a burger place,
and I'll order a double cheeseburger.

24:15.988 --> 24:17.122
I won't eat the bread.

24:17.222 --> 24:18.958
I won't eat the onions,
the tomato, the ketchup.

24:19.058 --> 24:21.060
I'll eat the meat, the cheese,
the mayo, the mustard,

24:21.160 --> 24:23.966
and I'll order up to three with,
like, three diet sodas.

24:24.296 --> 24:26.365
And people go, "That's unhealthy.

24:26.465 --> 24:28.500
"The cholesterol's gonna kill you."

24:28.600 --> 24:31.370
I agree. But guess what?

24:31.470 --> 24:33.472
Cholesterol's gonna take
10 years to kill me.

24:33.572 --> 24:35.007
Diabetes is going to do it in two.

24:35.107 --> 24:36.843
Right now, I'm winning by eight.

24:38.744 --> 24:40.548
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

24:43.349 --> 24:46.223
Hell, yeah. That's called
"Fluffy math," bro.

24:46.785 --> 24:48.320
There's a lot of people
mad in here right now.

24:48.420 --> 24:51.066
"Fluffy found a loophole." Yes.

24:51.423 --> 24:53.025
So I started low-carbing.

24:53.125 --> 24:56.595
I started doing yoga and I know
that sounds like a joke right there.

24:56.695 --> 24:58.664
Yeah, some of you are like,
"He means yogurt."

24:58.764 --> 25:01.367
No, yoga. Frigging DDP, help me.

25:01.467 --> 25:03.836
And then, uh, I started
lifting weights.

25:03.936 --> 25:05.604
And it's kind of hard
for me, you guys,

25:05.704 --> 25:07.907
because now I have people
at my shows telling me,

25:08.007 --> 25:10.009
"We're noticing there's
a little difference.

25:10.109 --> 25:12.044
"You're a little less fluffy.

25:12.144 --> 25:14.713
"What's going to happen
if you keep losing weight?

25:14.813 --> 25:16.181
"What are we going to call you?

25:16.281 --> 25:17.516
"What are we going to call you?"

25:17.616 --> 25:20.524
I lift weights. Call me
"Buffy." I don't care.

25:21.820 --> 25:24.690
The point is, is that I'm not trying
to lose weight for vanity's sake.

25:24.790 --> 25:25.858
I'm very secure.

25:25.958 --> 25:27.526
The point is that I'm
trying to lose weight

25:27.626 --> 25:30.396
so I can be around for my family,
so I can be around for my friends,

25:30.496 --> 25:32.598
and so I can be around for you.

25:32.698 --> 25:34.502
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

25:41.473 --> 25:43.108
I'm not trying to preach to nobody.

25:43.208 --> 25:44.643
"This is what you got
to do with your life."

25:44.743 --> 25:45.978
Hell, no. Shoot,
you like burgers? Kill it.

25:46.078 --> 25:47.621
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

25:48.380 --> 25:50.716
I'm just saying that's what I'm
going through. And then people think,

25:50.816 --> 25:53.719
"Oh, he's trying to lose weight,
because he's doing movies.

25:53.819 --> 25:56.989
"He wants to look better.
He wants to be accepted.

25:57.089 --> 25:59.391
"He wants to be accep..."
No, no, no, no.

25:59.491 --> 26:01.727
Don't get it twisted, you guys.
Don't even think that.

26:01.827 --> 26:05.230
At my highest weight of 445 pounds,

26:05.330 --> 26:09.234
the level of acceptance I
had was amazing, okay?

26:09.334 --> 26:11.170
To put it to you like this...

26:11.270 --> 26:12.574
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

26:14.206 --> 26:15.741
To put it to you like this,

26:15.841 --> 26:18.010
at 445 pounds,

26:18.110 --> 26:20.679
there was women throwing
themselves at me.

26:20.779 --> 26:23.050
At 445 pounds,

26:23.749 --> 26:25.485
there was men.

26:27.719 --> 26:32.061
Oh, and, Bay Area, let me tell
you something about gay men.

26:32.958 --> 26:35.832
I know you're in here.
I saw the line.

26:37.429 --> 26:39.164
I'm going to tell you
something about gay men.

26:39.264 --> 26:41.300
Gay men are very creative.

26:41.400 --> 26:44.970
They're very persistent,
and they're very opportunistic

26:45.070 --> 26:47.910
when they want to
achieve the mission.

26:49.808 --> 26:52.611
They're just as calculated
as straight men are.

26:52.711 --> 26:54.213
I'll give you an example.
I'll tell you a story, right?

26:54.313 --> 26:58.317
So one night, Martin and I are at
a bar, and we're having drinks,

26:58.417 --> 26:59.985
and that should come as no surprise.

27:00.085 --> 27:02.322
"Really? They were drinking?"
Yeah. We killed it. So...

27:03.255 --> 27:05.724
As we're drinking,
Martin is paying attention,

27:05.824 --> 27:08.460
and he's listening in to a
conversation that's happening

27:08.560 --> 27:11.397
about 15 feet away
between these two girls.

27:11.497 --> 27:13.832
They're going back and forth,
and one of 'em was like,

27:13.932 --> 27:17.569
(SLURRING) "I don't believe
we finished the whole bottle.

27:17.669 --> 27:21.442
"How the hell are we
supposed to get home?"

27:21.807 --> 27:24.810
Martin stands up,
looks at me, and says,

27:24.910 --> 27:27.454
"Bro, I'll be back."

27:28.981 --> 27:31.821
And then it began, the hunt.

27:32.017 --> 27:33.218
You know, freaking...

27:33.318 --> 27:35.293
(HUMMING THEME FROM JAWS)

27:40.993 --> 27:43.162
Gay men are the exact same way.

27:43.262 --> 27:45.497
They listen. They focus.
They pay attention.

27:45.597 --> 27:47.733
They wait for one of the cows to
get away from the rest of the herd,

27:47.833 --> 27:50.479
so they can corner it and strike.

27:51.103 --> 27:53.605
Four hours later,
Martin and I are at the bar,

27:53.705 --> 27:56.175
and I'm 16 shots of tequila in.

27:56.275 --> 27:57.242
AUDIENCE: Whoo!

27:57.342 --> 27:59.818
Oh, yeah, and I feel fantastic!

28:02.014 --> 28:04.716
And I tell Martin,
"Bro, I don't remember

28:04.816 --> 28:08.187
"the last time I had this
many shots of tequila."

28:08.287 --> 28:10.389
And Martin goes,
"Bro, you're crazy, Fluffy.

28:10.489 --> 28:13.025
"You're crazy. Wait right here.
I got to pee."

28:13.125 --> 28:14.626
And so he leaves to the restroom,

28:14.726 --> 28:16.595
and I'm leaning against the bar.

28:16.695 --> 28:18.931
The bar is the only thing
keeping me standing.

28:19.031 --> 28:21.700
And from across the room,
this guy stands up,

28:21.800 --> 28:24.970
looks at his friends,
and says, "I'll be back."

28:25.070 --> 28:26.681
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

28:36.715 --> 28:39.794
And then it began, the hunt.

28:40.986 --> 28:43.188
(HUMMING THEME FROM JAWS)

28:45.824 --> 28:47.059
(THUMPS)

28:47.159 --> 28:49.161
And he gets in my face,
and he tells me,

28:49.261 --> 28:52.397
"I just have to say I am
such a huge fan of yours.

28:52.497 --> 28:54.066
"Oh, my God!"

28:54.166 --> 28:57.436
Any time someone says
they're a huge fan of mine,

28:57.536 --> 28:59.571
it automatically makes me smile,

28:59.671 --> 29:01.908
even more so if I've been drinking.

29:02.841 --> 29:06.614
Oh, yeah, if I'm drinking,
I'm like, "Thank you. Thank you."

29:07.512 --> 29:10.716
Bro, I was so loaded,
I bowed. "Thank you."

29:16.888 --> 29:18.957
The guy puts his hand on my shoulder,

29:19.057 --> 29:20.926
and he says, "I just have to say

29:21.026 --> 29:22.828
"you have gotten me
through some difficult..."

29:22.928 --> 29:24.496
And he stops talking,

29:24.596 --> 29:28.642
and he squeezes,
and he goes, "Oh, my God!

29:30.535 --> 29:32.408
"Do you work out?"

29:34.273 --> 29:37.647
I was so drunk, I said, "A little.

29:40.646 --> 29:42.917
"You're the first person to notice!"

29:44.716 --> 29:46.151
And he's like,
"Oh, you can totally tell."

29:46.251 --> 29:48.120
And he squeezed again,
and I said... "Ahh."

29:48.220 --> 29:49.688
"I'm sorry. Am I overstepping?"

29:49.788 --> 29:51.456
"No, bro, you don't understand.

29:51.556 --> 29:54.327
"I'm stressed out.
That felt pretty good."

29:55.727 --> 29:57.029
"Want me to rub both your shoulders

29:57.129 --> 29:59.565
"and your back and scratch it?
'Cause I will."

29:59.665 --> 30:01.970
Oh. Whoa! (LAUGHS)

30:05.737 --> 30:07.280
"Hey, go for it."

30:09.574 --> 30:12.144
He grabs me by
the shoulders, you guys.

30:12.244 --> 30:15.647
He grabs me by the shoulders,
and he turns me around.

30:15.747 --> 30:17.749
Now I'm facing the bartender,

30:17.849 --> 30:20.352
and the bar-tender
is trying to warn me.

30:20.452 --> 30:23.531
The bartender's like, "Hello!

30:23.689 --> 30:25.960
"Hello!

30:26.525 --> 30:28.636
"Hello!

30:31.663 --> 30:33.638
"Hello!"

30:36.768 --> 30:39.676
I'm so drunk, I'm like... (SCREAMS)

30:41.840 --> 30:45.043
This guy is working my neck well.

30:45.143 --> 30:46.822
I'm like... (GRUNTING)

30:48.313 --> 30:51.153
It feels so good, I push off the bar.

30:52.284 --> 30:55.354
At that moment,
Martin returns from the restroom.

30:55.454 --> 30:57.089
He sees what's going on.

30:57.189 --> 30:59.591
He doesn't stop it.
He doesn't say a word.

30:59.691 --> 31:03.065
As far as I know,
"Machete" is taking notes.

31:05.731 --> 31:07.599
The guy turns me back
around, and he says,

31:07.699 --> 31:10.936
"I just have to say,
if you were mine,

31:11.036 --> 31:15.378
"I would cook for you every
single day of your life."

31:16.408 --> 31:18.977
At that moment,
Martin cuts into the conversation

31:19.077 --> 31:21.246
like a referee at the
end of a bad fight,

31:21.346 --> 31:22.781
and he hugs me, and he holds me,

31:22.881 --> 31:25.083
and he goes, "Dude,"
and I go, "Dude,"

31:25.183 --> 31:26.618
and then I looked at the guy.

31:26.718 --> 31:28.955
"Hey, what can you cook?"

31:30.255 --> 31:32.090
And Martin shook me.
"Gabriel." "What?"

31:32.190 --> 31:34.393
And he drags me away, and I go,

31:34.493 --> 31:36.795
"Martin, what are you doing, bro?

31:36.895 --> 31:39.097
"You can't do that. That's rude."

31:39.197 --> 31:41.733
He goes, "Dude, that guy was
trying to hook up with you."

31:41.833 --> 31:44.336
"No, Martin. No.

31:44.436 --> 31:46.946
"He was trying to feed me.

31:48.173 --> 31:51.081
"Why are you always
food-blocking, bro?"

31:51.543 --> 31:53.812
"I'm your friend,
I'm your friend, Gabriel."

31:53.912 --> 31:57.082
"You're not my friend!
You're not my friend!

31:57.182 --> 32:00.329
"When's the last time you
rubbed my shoulders, huh?

32:00.852 --> 32:03.755
"When's the last time you said,
'Fluffy, I'll cook for you'?

32:03.855 --> 32:07.298
"You don't cook for me!
You made me throw away muffins!"

32:09.428 --> 32:11.463
We're arguing so hard, you guys,

32:11.563 --> 32:14.073
now this guy thinks we're gay.

32:15.100 --> 32:17.169
He's like, "Oh, my God.
I'm such a home-wrecker."

32:17.269 --> 32:19.073
And then he ran.

32:21.940 --> 32:24.279
The point to that story is, (LAUGHS)

32:25.944 --> 32:29.091
I started losing weight
for health reasons.

32:30.715 --> 32:33.259
Some of you are like,
"He went a little far for that."

32:33.418 --> 32:34.858
Poquito.

32:35.654 --> 32:39.458
What I think is funny is that now
people are questioning my shows.

32:39.558 --> 32:42.494
They're like, "Well, what is
Gabriel going to talk about

32:42.594 --> 32:44.463
"if he continues to lose weight?

32:44.563 --> 32:46.208
"What's he going to talk about?"

32:46.731 --> 32:48.500
I'm like, seriously,
between the amount

32:48.600 --> 32:50.635
of crazy friends that I have

32:50.735 --> 32:53.572
and the amount of alcohol
I drink on a regular basis

32:53.672 --> 32:56.808
and the amount of crazy,
random places we visit,

32:56.908 --> 32:59.211
I will always have
stories for you guys.

32:59.311 --> 33:00.846
Random stories.

33:00.946 --> 33:02.557
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

33:08.153 --> 33:10.088
Stories no one else has.

33:10.188 --> 33:13.801
Stories like Martin and I
just got back from India.

33:14.759 --> 33:16.063
Yeah.

33:16.595 --> 33:19.931
So let me tell you, I started
posting on Facebook and Twitter

33:20.031 --> 33:22.000
that we were going to go
out there to do these shows,

33:22.100 --> 33:24.403
and then people started
sending me messages,

33:24.503 --> 33:26.171
questioning what I was going to do.

33:26.271 --> 33:30.008
First of all, "Are they gonna
understand you in India?

33:30.108 --> 33:31.910
"Will they understand English okay?

33:32.010 --> 33:34.946
"Will they be able to follow
along with your stories?"

33:35.046 --> 33:37.249
Once we got there, I come to find out

33:37.349 --> 33:40.018
that more people speak
English in India

33:40.118 --> 33:44.189
than in all of the US and
Canada put together.

33:44.289 --> 33:47.834
Might as well throw Mexico
in there for extra credit.

33:48.293 --> 33:49.728
Because there's that many people,

33:49.828 --> 33:51.430
and, yes, they have the Internet.

33:51.530 --> 33:53.732
They got the Internet.
They got Bollywood. They got Hollywood.

33:53.832 --> 33:55.901
They understand American culture

33:56.001 --> 33:58.970
so much more than we
understand theirs.

33:59.070 --> 34:02.441
Second thing, people tried to
warn me about going over there.

34:02.541 --> 34:06.812
"Gabriel, be careful.
India is a Third World country,

34:06.912 --> 34:08.713
"Don't drink the water in India.

34:08.813 --> 34:11.882
"It contains parasites that'll
make you really sick.

34:11.983 --> 34:15.554
"Don't eat the food from the street
people, especially the street meat.

34:15.654 --> 34:18.723
"It contains a parasite
that'll make you really sick.

34:18.822 --> 34:21.927
"And most importantly,
there's a lot of crime over there.

34:22.027 --> 34:24.496
"Don't stay out late.
When the sun goes down,

34:24.596 --> 34:26.469
(WHISPERS) "you go down."

34:27.831 --> 34:29.601
I'm like, "Is it that bad?"

34:29.701 --> 34:31.312
(WHISPERS) "Parasites."

34:32.337 --> 34:33.804
So I'm like, "Let me
get this straight.

34:33.905 --> 34:36.141
"There's a lot of crime.
Don't stay out late.

34:36.241 --> 34:38.577
"Don't eat any of the food
from the street vendors,

34:38.677 --> 34:40.946
"and don't drink the water.

34:41.045 --> 34:43.281
"Why does that sound familiar?

34:43.380 --> 34:45.150
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

34:47.118 --> 34:48.956
"That's Mexico!"

34:49.454 --> 34:51.429
(ALL CHEERING)

34:57.862 --> 34:59.798
When Martin and I got over there,

34:59.898 --> 35:03.535
we found out that Indian
people and Mexican people

35:03.635 --> 35:05.937
have so much in common, you guys.

35:06.037 --> 35:10.709
I'm telling you it's insane how
similar we are, especially the food.

35:10.809 --> 35:12.277
The food is so similar.

35:12.377 --> 35:15.447
For example, Mexicans love tortillas.

35:15.547 --> 35:17.949
Indian people love naan bread,

35:18.049 --> 35:20.952
which is a fluffier
form of a tortilla.

35:21.052 --> 35:23.722
Mexicans love chicken.
Indians love chicken.

35:23.822 --> 35:25.557
Mexicans love hot and spicy.

35:25.657 --> 35:28.627
Indians invented hot and spicy.

35:28.727 --> 35:31.630
Most popular drink
in Mexico is Fanta.

35:31.730 --> 35:34.466
Most popular drink in India is Fanta.

35:34.566 --> 35:36.334
Indian people worship cows.

35:36.434 --> 35:38.614
Mexicans love barbecues.

35:40.739 --> 35:42.714
Lot of similarities.

35:43.408 --> 35:44.976
Most of the people
that I met over there

35:45.076 --> 35:47.479
were very hardworking and humble,

35:47.579 --> 35:50.015
and I got to tell you,
every time I talked to someone,

35:50.115 --> 35:51.650
I was always greeted the same way.

35:51.750 --> 35:53.818
They'd look at me,
they'd put their hands together,

35:53.918 --> 35:57.531
they'd do a little bow,
and they say, "Namaste,"

35:57.989 --> 35:59.991
which is an endearing hello.

36:00.091 --> 36:01.693
It's really nice and sweet.

36:01.793 --> 36:04.829
And then I noticed that Indian people,
when you're talking to them,

36:04.929 --> 36:06.498
do this thing with their head,

36:06.598 --> 36:11.338
where it will begin to move side
to side as they're speaking.

36:11.670 --> 36:13.171
Now, at first, when you
notice it, you think,

36:13.271 --> 36:15.075
"Oh, he slept wrong.

36:15.273 --> 36:18.886
"He just got a kink in his neck.
Get a Tempur-Pedic!"

36:20.278 --> 36:21.846
Now, when they start speaking,

36:21.946 --> 36:23.081
their head starts moving,
and I noticed this.

36:23.181 --> 36:26.084
The guy is checking us in to
the hotel, and he's really cool.

36:26.184 --> 36:28.753
He's like, (INDIAN ACCENT) "Listen,
if you have any problems at all, okay,

36:28.853 --> 36:30.522
"you call the front desk,
you press zero.

36:30.622 --> 36:32.424
"We will send somebody to
your room to help you.

36:32.524 --> 36:34.225
"Whatever you need, we got it for you

36:34.325 --> 36:35.927
"right here, okay? It's very good."

36:36.027 --> 36:38.363
Now, one thing I notice
is the more they talk

36:38.463 --> 36:40.865
and the more excited
Indian people get,

36:40.965 --> 36:43.468
the more the head
starts to move around.

36:43.568 --> 36:46.204
Somebody at the hotel
yelled out to the clerk,

36:46.304 --> 36:47.639
"That's Fluffy."
And the guy was like,

36:47.739 --> 36:49.074
(INDIAN ACCENT)
"Oh, my God! I don't believe it.

36:49.174 --> 36:51.376
"I knew it. I thought it was you.
I thought it was you.

36:51.476 --> 36:52.978
"Oh, my God! I cannot believe it.
This is so crazy.

36:53.078 --> 36:54.780
"Oh, my God, Fluffy. Fluffy! Fluffy!"

36:56.414 --> 37:01.393
Even crazier than that is that the
mouth is actually connected to the neck.

37:01.820 --> 37:03.388
When the mouth stops moving,

37:03.488 --> 37:05.991
the head stops wherever
the mouth left off.

37:06.091 --> 37:08.960
And when you see Indian people
talking to each other, you can see it.

37:09.060 --> 37:10.629
(INDIAN ACCENT) "Okay, let me tell
you something. Okay. Correct.

37:10.729 --> 37:13.565
"Oh, okay. Hold up. Wait. Wait. Wait.
Wait. Wait. Hold on. Wait. Okay."

37:13.665 --> 37:17.039
Like, if you're Indian, and you
stutter, you are so screwed.

37:18.169 --> 37:21.172
(STUTTERING) "I... I... I..."

37:21.272 --> 37:23.247
"Somebody stop him!"

37:23.908 --> 37:25.553
(ALL LAUGHING)

37:28.379 --> 37:29.781
I'm not going to lie, you guys.

37:29.881 --> 37:33.893
When I first saw this happen,
I thought it was hysterical.

37:34.352 --> 37:36.187
I thought it was funny.

37:36.287 --> 37:38.123
But then I started thinking about it.

37:38.223 --> 37:41.092
Head movement is just
a form of expression.

37:41.192 --> 37:43.428
No matter where you
live in this world,

37:43.528 --> 37:47.032
people express themselves
in their own unique way,

37:47.132 --> 37:49.434
whether through facial expressions,

37:49.534 --> 37:53.038
hand gestures,
body movement, extra words.

37:53.138 --> 37:55.540
Everywhere you go,
things are different,

37:55.640 --> 37:58.810
and that's just how they
express themselves in India.

37:58.910 --> 38:01.279
Now back to the whole
Indians-Mexican thing.

38:01.379 --> 38:05.316
That is something else that we
share in common with Indian people.

38:05.416 --> 38:06.451
Head movement.

38:06.551 --> 38:08.119
Now, some of you in the
building tonight are like,

38:08.219 --> 38:10.989
"Stupid. We don't
have head movement."

38:11.089 --> 38:13.158
Yes, we do. It's a little different.

38:13.258 --> 38:17.270
See, with Indian people,
the head movement is side to side.

38:17.729 --> 38:21.433
Mexicans, our head
movement is front to back.

38:23.735 --> 38:28.973
The difference between that is that with
Mexicans, we have to be very, very upset

38:29.073 --> 38:31.076
in order for you to see
the head movement.

38:31.176 --> 38:32.644
Otherwise, you can't tell.

38:32.744 --> 38:34.813
With Indians, it's all the time.

38:34.913 --> 38:36.915
(INDIAN ACCENT)
"Oh, today is such a nice day.

38:37.015 --> 38:39.050
"It is such a beautiful day today.

38:39.150 --> 38:41.019
"I am so happy.
It's very nice, very good.

38:41.119 --> 38:43.822
"Oh, my God. I can't believe it's
so nice. It's such a pretty..."

38:43.922 --> 38:46.925
Mexicans, when we're mad,
that's when it comes out.

38:47.025 --> 38:48.593
For non-Latinos, hey, trust me.

38:48.693 --> 38:50.995
You cut off a Mexican in traffic,
see what happens.

38:51.095 --> 38:52.330
(MIMICS CAR PASSING)

38:52.430 --> 38:54.007
(YELLING IN SPANISH)

38:58.603 --> 39:00.009
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

39:05.443 --> 39:07.779
That's funny. I don't know why
the black people are laughing.

39:07.879 --> 39:09.180
You guys take it all.

39:09.280 --> 39:11.416
"Oh, no, you didn't. Oh, hell, no!

39:11.516 --> 39:13.351
"I know he ain't talkin' 'bout me!

39:13.451 --> 39:16.825
"Uh-Uh. I hear the bell!
I hear the bell!"

39:21.726 --> 39:24.236
I made myself dizzy doing that.
(LAUGHS)

39:28.566 --> 39:30.368
So let me tell you guys.

39:30.468 --> 39:33.772
If you ever get the opportunity

39:33.872 --> 39:36.177
to travel to India,

39:36.574 --> 39:38.443
I encourage you to check it out.

39:38.543 --> 39:41.379
You are going to see
some beautiful things.

39:41.479 --> 39:43.715
You are going to see
some amazing things.

39:43.815 --> 39:46.618
You are going to see some sad,
depressing things

39:46.718 --> 39:49.053
and some real horrible things.

39:49.153 --> 39:52.061
Overall, it's a well-balanced trip.

39:53.358 --> 39:56.261
But when you get back home
here to the United States,

39:56.361 --> 40:00.565
you will have a whole different
appreciation for your life.

40:00.665 --> 40:02.367
- Believe that.
- (AUDIENCE CHEERING)

40:03.034 --> 40:05.214
I guarantee this, you guys.

40:06.037 --> 40:07.739
There's a lot of people in India,

40:07.839 --> 40:10.909
and with a lot of people
comes a lot of traffic.

40:11.009 --> 40:11.976
First things first.

40:12.076 --> 40:15.621
American traffic and Indian traffic,
very different.

40:16.281 --> 40:18.416
Here, whatever happens on the freeway

40:18.516 --> 40:20.559
will stop the whole freeway.

40:20.852 --> 40:24.465
In India, there's 10 times
the traffic, but it moves.

40:26.190 --> 40:28.693
See, the problem is Americans,
we're fascinated by accidents.

40:28.793 --> 40:31.473
We're fascinated by the idea
of seeing potential death.

40:32.697 --> 40:34.432
That's why we slow
down on the freeways.

40:34.532 --> 40:37.001
We say we don't want to see it,
but what happens in traffic?

40:37.101 --> 40:38.303
You know...
(MIMICS BRAKES SCREECHING)

40:38.403 --> 40:40.139
"What's going on over there?"

40:41.039 --> 40:42.741
(MURMURING)

40:43.942 --> 40:45.977
There doesn't even
have to be a collision.

40:46.077 --> 40:47.445
You could be on the 101 freeway

40:47.545 --> 40:50.381
and a car has a tire
blowout, and it spins.

40:50.481 --> 40:52.116
(MIMICS TIRES SCREECHING)

40:52.216 --> 40:53.384
Doesn't hit anything.

40:53.484 --> 40:55.820
It's now facing oncoming traffic.

40:55.920 --> 40:57.997
You know what happens to
the rest of the freeway?

40:58.323 --> 41:00.366
(MIMICS BRAKES SQUEALING)

41:00.725 --> 41:03.769
Even on the other freeway,
where there's no accident.

41:04.295 --> 41:05.663
(MIMICS BRAKES SQUEALING)

41:05.763 --> 41:09.000
And again, "Why? What's going on?
What's going on?"

41:09.100 --> 41:10.134
(MIMICS HONKING)

41:10.234 --> 41:14.277
"I'm sorry. Hey, somebody might
be dead. Sorry. Oh."

41:15.907 --> 41:17.742
In India, if there's an accident

41:17.842 --> 41:19.911
in the middle of the street,
you know what they do?

41:20.011 --> 41:23.014
They drive right around it.
They don't stop.

41:23.114 --> 41:25.750
And it's not that they're not
sensitive to the situation.

41:25.850 --> 41:27.685
They are. It's just that
there's so much chaos

41:27.785 --> 41:29.554
that happens on a regular basis,

41:29.654 --> 41:31.155
they just need to get to work.

41:31.255 --> 41:32.523
They do see what's happening,

41:32.623 --> 41:34.192
and, believe me,
they're heartfelt, you know.

41:34.292 --> 41:35.835
They'll drive around, you know.
(MIMICS CAR PASSING)

41:35.960 --> 41:37.537
(INDIAN ACCENT)
"I am so sorry for you."

41:37.929 --> 41:39.472
(MIMICS CAR DRIVING AWAY)

41:40.498 --> 41:44.168
Nothing stops the flow
of traffic in India.

41:44.268 --> 41:48.239
They need to get from point A to
point B, and so they go. They go.

41:48.339 --> 41:49.574
If there's an accident,
they drive around.

41:49.674 --> 41:51.075
If there's something
blocking the street,

41:51.175 --> 41:53.578
they get on the
sidewalk to go around.

41:53.678 --> 41:55.380
It's amazing, the way they drive.

41:55.480 --> 41:56.915
And here's something else.

41:57.015 --> 41:59.183
No one uses turn signals over there.

41:59.283 --> 42:01.753
No one uses turn signals.

42:01.853 --> 42:03.521
They use a horn.

42:03.621 --> 42:05.023
Now, if you go to India tomorrow,

42:05.123 --> 42:06.858
from the time you get there
to the time you leave,

42:06.958 --> 42:08.927
you're constantly
going to hear a horn.

42:09.027 --> 42:11.896
It's an actual language
when people are driving.

42:11.996 --> 42:13.504
I'll show you. You're driving.

42:13.731 --> 42:14.732
(MIMICS HONKING)

42:14.832 --> 42:16.200
Car on your right. (HONKS ONCE)

42:16.300 --> 42:17.568
Car on your left. (HONKS THRICE)

42:17.668 --> 42:18.703
Light up ahead.

42:18.803 --> 42:20.538
They talk to each other
while they're driving,

42:20.638 --> 42:24.609
and they barely miss each
other every single time.

42:24.709 --> 42:27.045
Also, you'll be on the
101 freeway here,

42:27.145 --> 42:28.579
and there'll be six lanes.

42:28.679 --> 42:30.882
In India, you'll see six lanes,
but guess what?

42:30.982 --> 42:32.786
You'll see 12 cars across.

42:34.018 --> 42:36.554
Yes, they have lines, but they're
basically there to let you know

42:36.654 --> 42:39.130
more or less the direction
you might want to go in.

42:40.158 --> 42:41.926
They're this close to each other,

42:42.026 --> 42:43.895
and even at the light,
they communicate.

42:43.995 --> 42:45.163
(MIMICS CAR PASSING)

42:45.263 --> 42:46.264
You see everything,

42:46.364 --> 42:48.933
cars, trucks, vans,
motorcycles, pedestrians,

42:49.033 --> 42:51.804
cows, children,
all waiting for the light.

42:54.605 --> 42:56.975
And they talk at the light with
the horn. (MIMICS HONKING)

42:57.075 --> 42:59.744
(INDIAN ACCENT) "Very good. You can go.
You can go." (MIMICS HONKING)

42:59.844 --> 43:01.785
(INDIAN ACCENT)
"Welcome. You're welcome. Go, go."

43:03.614 --> 43:06.150
Nothing stops the flow
of traffic over there.

43:06.250 --> 43:09.687
Indian people drive... Think of ants.

43:09.787 --> 43:12.023
You know how ants travel
in a straight line,

43:12.123 --> 43:15.927
and if there's something in the way,
like a rock, ants will split up,

43:16.027 --> 43:19.263
go around the rock, and reunite,
or climb over the rock.

43:19.363 --> 43:22.633
Worst-case scenario, they dig
a hole and go under the rock.

43:22.733 --> 43:25.436
That's the mentality
of driving in India.

43:25.536 --> 43:29.115
A man can get shot in
the middle of the street.

43:29.273 --> 43:30.474
(MIMICS GUNSHOT)

43:31.309 --> 43:32.643
People just look at each other.

43:32.743 --> 43:34.923
(INDIAN ACCENT)
"Somebody pick him up."

43:35.880 --> 43:38.016
And they'll drag his
ass onto the sidewalk,

43:38.116 --> 43:40.351
and if there's an accident
and they need to get around,

43:40.451 --> 43:42.620
guess what's going to happen
to that guy on the sidewalk.

43:42.720 --> 43:44.194
(MIMICS CAR PASSING)

43:45.723 --> 43:48.960
Nothing stops the flow
of traffic in India,

43:49.060 --> 43:51.297
except a cow.

43:52.763 --> 43:55.366
Now, I know we've always heard
the stories and the jokes about,

43:55.466 --> 43:57.301
"Oh, Indian people
don't eat hamburgers."

43:57.401 --> 43:59.804
I asked the question,
and I found out.

43:59.904 --> 44:03.808
It's believed that cows
are people who have died,

44:03.908 --> 44:05.576
and they've been reincarnated,

44:05.676 --> 44:07.812
and their new life is now the cow,

44:07.912 --> 44:09.380
which is why they don't eat them

44:09.480 --> 44:12.550
and why they give 'em all the love
and respect in the world over there.

44:12.650 --> 44:14.318
I saw this firsthand.

44:14.418 --> 44:17.321
There's a cow crossing the
street while we're driving.

44:17.421 --> 44:18.856
And the cows know. They're cocky.

44:18.956 --> 44:21.295
They know that they can cross.

44:21.492 --> 44:23.061
Frigging... (MIMICS COW MOOING)

44:23.161 --> 44:25.307
All the cars...
(MIMICS BRAKES SQUEALING)

44:25.429 --> 44:28.408
And the cow's out there all cocky.
(MIMICS COW MOOING)

44:31.369 --> 44:33.139
(MIMICS BELL CLINKING)

44:35.506 --> 44:37.341
No one honks at the cows.

44:37.441 --> 44:39.911
No one yells at the cows.
No one touches the cows.

44:40.011 --> 44:42.513
They wait for the cows
to finish crossing.

44:42.613 --> 44:45.054
The cow that we had laid down.

44:46.617 --> 44:49.229
The driver just shut off the car.

44:49.787 --> 44:51.622
Started tweeting.

44:51.722 --> 44:54.025
(INDIAN ACCENT) "There is a cow

44:54.125 --> 44:55.998
"in the middle of the street.

44:57.228 --> 44:58.896
(MIMICS CLICKING)

44:58.996 --> 45:00.698
"#moomoo."

45:00.798 --> 45:02.341
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

45:06.470 --> 45:09.107
I asked the driver,
"What's going on?"

45:09.207 --> 45:11.216
(INDIAN ACCENT)
"Sir, there is a cow."

45:11.642 --> 45:13.111
(NORMAL VOICE)
"I see that there's a cow.

45:13.211 --> 45:15.746
"Are you going to honk at it, go around?
What's going to happen?"

45:15.846 --> 45:19.283
(INDIAN ACCENT) "We cannot...
We cannot honk at the cow.

45:19.383 --> 45:21.688
"We must wait for the cow to move."

45:22.086 --> 45:23.488
(NORMAL VOICE) "You're kidding."

45:23.588 --> 45:26.132
(INDIAN ACCENT) "I am not kidding.
We must wait for the cow,"

45:27.592 --> 45:31.638
(NORMAL VOICE) "We drove past
a dead body 15 minutes ago."

45:32.730 --> 45:34.632
(INDIAN ACCENT)
"That is probably him."

45:34.732 --> 45:36.206
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

45:45.443 --> 45:47.612
Like, seriously, the driving
situation over there

45:47.712 --> 45:49.814
is so intense, you guys.

45:49.914 --> 45:51.949
One morning, one morning
while we're there,

45:52.049 --> 45:55.019
I needed to get to the airport fast,
because I overslept,

45:55.119 --> 45:56.454
and so I get in the cab,

45:56.554 --> 45:58.856
and I hand the driver a $50 bill,

45:58.956 --> 46:01.259
and I go, "Sir,
I am running very late.

46:01.359 --> 46:03.828
"I need to get to the
airport as soon as possible.

46:03.928 --> 46:05.630
"Whatever side street
you have to take

46:05.730 --> 46:07.298
"or back road, I'm all for it.

46:07.398 --> 46:10.168
"Whatever you have
to do, let's do it."

46:10.268 --> 46:11.435
And I hand him the money,
and he goes,

46:11.535 --> 46:13.671
(INDIAN ACCENT) "Very good.
Let's go," and we take off.

46:13.771 --> 46:14.939
(MIMICS CAR PASSING)

46:15.039 --> 46:16.774
The guy is hitting anywhere from

46:16.874 --> 46:19.680
50 to 70 miles an hour on the street.

46:19.810 --> 46:22.422
We are making incredible time.

46:22.647 --> 46:24.520
(MIMICS CAR PASSING)

46:24.882 --> 46:28.791
I notice that we're heading in
the direction of a red light.

46:30.087 --> 46:33.097
Have you ever been
in a car with someone,

46:33.291 --> 46:35.726
and you're paying attention
to what's going on,

46:35.826 --> 46:38.629
and you notice that you're
about to hit a red light?

46:38.729 --> 46:41.065
And you know how you start
to mentally and physically

46:41.165 --> 46:45.303
prepare yourself for the
deceleration of the car

46:45.403 --> 46:48.472
and you start anticipating
the pressure from the brake?

46:48.572 --> 46:50.007
And if you don't get the sensation

46:50.107 --> 46:52.310
of slowing down by a certain point,

46:52.410 --> 46:54.145
all alarms go off in your head,

46:54.245 --> 46:56.147
and you sock the driver in the chest.

46:56.247 --> 46:57.619
"Hey!"

46:59.250 --> 47:01.519
Not only did I not get the sensation

47:01.619 --> 47:04.155
of slowing down, I got the opposite.

47:04.255 --> 47:06.824
He gunned it towards the light,

47:06.924 --> 47:08.092
and it caught me off-guard.

47:08.192 --> 47:10.328
I couldn't even scream. I was like...

47:10.428 --> 47:11.834
(CHOKING)

47:12.630 --> 47:14.098
And then... (MIMICS CAR PASSING)

47:14.198 --> 47:15.566
And then I got air.

47:15.666 --> 47:18.642
"Hey! Pull over! Pull over!"

47:19.603 --> 47:22.840
(MIMICS BRAKES SCREECHING)
He didn't even know what he did.

47:22.940 --> 47:24.075
He looks at me. He goes,

47:24.175 --> 47:25.979
(INDIAN ACCENT) "What is wrong?"

47:26.811 --> 47:28.379
(NORMAL VOICE)
"What do you mean, 'What is wrong?'

47:28.479 --> 47:30.681
"Dude, didn't you see the red light?"

47:30.781 --> 47:32.416
As calm as can be,

47:32.516 --> 47:35.492
(INDIAN ACCENT) "Didn't you
see there was no one there?

47:38.956 --> 47:41.892
"You told me, 'Whatever
you have to do,' okay?

47:41.992 --> 47:45.002
"Whatever you have to do, you do.'

47:46.063 --> 47:49.437
"Do you want to yell,
or do you want to make plane?"

47:49.700 --> 47:51.769
He made a good point.
I sounded like a third-grader.

47:51.869 --> 47:54.015
"I want to make plane."

47:54.839 --> 47:57.308
Like, seriously, that's a
video game I want to see.

47:57.408 --> 47:59.910
I want to see Grand Theft Auto India.

48:00.010 --> 48:01.518
(ALL LAUGHING)

48:07.318 --> 48:09.720
By the way, uh,
since my last special,

48:09.820 --> 48:13.092
I gotta tell you something
about my son Frankie.

48:13.324 --> 48:18.030
He now, now, wears deodorant.

48:18.529 --> 48:20.208
(ALL CHEERING)

48:26.570 --> 48:28.806
Now for the rest of you
that are watching right now,

48:28.906 --> 48:30.908
wondering, "What is
he talking about?"

48:31.008 --> 48:32.476
And the people watching
the movie, going,

48:32.576 --> 48:34.578
"I don't get this," let me explain.

48:34.678 --> 48:37.682
In my last special, I made
reference to my son Frankie

48:37.782 --> 48:41.619
and how he refuses to
regularly put deodorant on.

48:41.719 --> 48:43.754
And so I told him,
"If you don't start doing it,

48:43.854 --> 48:45.923
"I'm going put your business on TV,

48:46.023 --> 48:47.925
"and your friends are going
to see me talking about you,

48:48.025 --> 48:50.094
"and they're going to
check you for me."

48:50.194 --> 48:52.663
Sure enough, my last special airs.

48:52.763 --> 48:54.765
The next day, Frankie goes to school,

48:54.865 --> 48:57.409
and those kids were merciless.

48:58.102 --> 49:00.638
He came home.
He takes off his backpack.

49:00.738 --> 49:02.640
He unzips it, and he dumps out,

49:02.740 --> 49:04.775
like, 17 deodorants.

49:04.875 --> 49:06.986
"See what you did!"

49:08.379 --> 49:12.152
I was like, "Wow, look at all
the money we just saved."

49:13.717 --> 49:15.453
His mom was impressed.

49:15.553 --> 49:18.757
She was like, "Talk about
how he needs towels."

49:19.824 --> 49:22.664
Hell, yeah. He's going to get towels.
(LAUGHS)

49:24.161 --> 49:25.463
And it's funny, because,

49:25.563 --> 49:27.398
you know, for me to relate to my son,

49:27.498 --> 49:29.467
it's a little challenging, you guys.

49:29.567 --> 49:32.136
It's not that I can't relate
to a teenager, because I can.

49:32.236 --> 49:33.671
I can relate to almost any age.

49:33.771 --> 49:35.673
You know, I got people that
brought kids here tonight.

49:35.773 --> 49:39.910
The problem is, is that my son
doesn't see me as an entertainer.

49:40.010 --> 49:42.313
He sees me as the guy that
tells him to take a shower,

49:42.413 --> 49:45.649
put on deodorant, you know,
"Stop picking your nose," That's me.

49:45.749 --> 49:47.852
His friends, on the other hand,

49:47.952 --> 49:50.254
I'm like a god to his friends.

49:50.354 --> 49:53.424
Every time I drop off Frankie at
school now, I pull up, you know.

49:53.524 --> 49:55.159
(MIMICS BRAKES SCREECHING)

49:55.259 --> 49:56.927
The kids see my car.

49:57.027 --> 49:59.230
They freak out,
and they run over to it,

49:59.330 --> 50:02.400
and they put their hands
on it like it's a shrine.

50:02.500 --> 50:03.901
They touch the car like freaking,

50:04.001 --> 50:06.010
"Selena está aquí," you know?

50:07.171 --> 50:08.339
Some of you got that. Gracias.

50:08.439 --> 50:09.913
Anyway...

50:11.041 --> 50:15.613
Then the kids start shaking
my car side to side, chanting,

50:15.713 --> 50:18.716
"Fluffy. Fluffy. Fluffy."

50:18.816 --> 50:22.186
And Frankie's in the front
seat pissed. He's pissed.

50:22.286 --> 50:24.830
He's like, "This is bullshit."

50:25.990 --> 50:27.691
I'm like, "Hey, dude,
don't get mad at me,

50:27.791 --> 50:30.728
"cause I'm more popular
than you at your school."

50:30.828 --> 50:32.268
Little hater. (LAUGHS)

50:33.163 --> 50:35.266
He gets out of the car all mad.
(MIMICS SHUTTING DOOR)

50:35.366 --> 50:36.700
(MUMBLING)

50:36.800 --> 50:40.038
They're still chanting.
"Fluffy, Fluffy."

50:41.572 --> 50:43.941
The thing is, is that our
worlds are very different.

50:44.041 --> 50:45.810
His world revolves around

50:45.910 --> 50:47.783
Grand Theft Auto, the video game,

50:48.579 --> 50:50.850
YouTube and girls.

50:51.015 --> 50:53.354
He's really good at two of those.

50:54.485 --> 50:56.858
The other one, not so much.

50:57.321 --> 50:59.089
And it's not that I'm trying
to be a hater about it.

50:59.189 --> 51:00.458
It's just that I tell Frankie,

51:00.558 --> 51:03.561
"Listen, you need to start
having more conversations.

51:03.661 --> 51:06.397
"You need to become more
talkative and interact like this."

51:06.497 --> 51:09.066
See, he'd rather text than talk.

51:09.166 --> 51:10.134
That's his whole thing. I'm like,

51:10.234 --> 51:11.802
"Dude, you got to learn,
you know, start...

51:11.902 --> 51:14.171
"Talk to me! I wish you
would talk to me more.

51:14.271 --> 51:16.307
"You could learn a lot about
talking by talking to me.

51:16.407 --> 51:19.747
"I'm just saying, I only
do it professionally."

51:20.444 --> 51:22.079
But, no, he'd rather text.

51:22.179 --> 51:24.748
It's at the point now where
if I'm in the house and I yell,

51:24.848 --> 51:28.252
"Frankie, did you
take out the trash?"

51:28.352 --> 51:30.421
Nothing. All of a sudden...

51:30.521 --> 51:31.989
(MIMICS PHONE CHIMING)

51:32.089 --> 51:33.290
I take out my phone.

51:33.390 --> 51:34.796
"No."

51:35.926 --> 51:37.928
But if I say, "I got money for you,"

51:38.028 --> 51:40.799
freaking Houdini, right? "Oh, hello."

51:41.632 --> 51:43.743
'Cause you can't text cash.

51:45.102 --> 51:47.638
That's my big thing right now.
I just want him to take out the trash.

51:47.738 --> 51:48.939
He's 16 years old now.

51:49.039 --> 51:50.174
He should have been doing
this since he was 10,

51:50.274 --> 51:51.842
but, you know,
better late than never.

51:51.942 --> 51:54.278
And what he does is he'll
sit in the living room,

51:54.378 --> 51:56.847
and he tunes out the
rest of the house.

51:56.947 --> 51:59.116
He sits there, and he'll
put on these headphones

51:59.216 --> 52:01.352
that I got him for Christmas
a couple of years ago,

52:01.452 --> 52:03.621
these Beats with the
freaking studio button,

52:03.721 --> 52:06.290
and it cuts out all of the sound.

52:06.390 --> 52:07.791
They are so strong

52:07.891 --> 52:10.294
that when he starts watching
his YouTube videos,

52:10.394 --> 52:12.830
he can't hear himself laugh.

52:12.930 --> 52:16.000
And for me, that is the
funniest thing in the world.

52:16.100 --> 52:18.202
I'm in the other room,
and I can hear him.

52:18.302 --> 52:20.137
This is what I hear...

52:20.237 --> 52:21.882
(GROANING)

52:29.947 --> 52:31.353
(SCREAMING)

52:32.850 --> 52:36.520
I'm in the other room, like,
"Who brought the Germans?"

52:39.757 --> 52:41.992
And so I walk out into the
living room, and I see Frankie,

52:42.092 --> 52:43.494
and he's laughing at his phone,

52:43.594 --> 52:45.396
and I got to flag him down.
"Hey, hey, hey."

52:45.496 --> 52:47.831
And he'll take 'em off.
"What? What's up, Dad?"

52:47.931 --> 52:50.267
I go, "Frankie,
can you do me a favor?

52:50.367 --> 52:53.846
"Can you please take out the trash?"
"Okay." And then he puts 'em back on.

52:57.775 --> 52:59.477
"What?

52:59.843 --> 53:01.345
"Now?"

53:01.445 --> 53:03.750
I go, "Yes, now.

53:04.214 --> 53:06.283
"When you ask me for a ride,
it's because you need a ride

53:06.383 --> 53:08.118
"when you ask for a ride, not later."

53:08.218 --> 53:10.398
Then he says, "Where are we going?"

53:11.789 --> 53:13.691
"Just take out the trash."

53:13.791 --> 53:15.626
And then he does it.
He takes out the trash,

53:15.726 --> 53:18.862
but he acts like he's doing me
the biggest favor in the world,

53:18.962 --> 53:21.632
and he stares me down,
and he doesn't break eye contact,

53:21.732 --> 53:23.377
He's like... (SIGHING)

53:28.839 --> 53:31.713
And then he'll hold the bag over
the can, and he makes the sound...

53:32.009 --> 53:33.449
(LOUD SIGH)

53:33.877 --> 53:35.852
I'm like, "Dude, so much drama."

53:37.214 --> 53:39.783
It's crazy. I'd like to have
normal conversations with him,

53:39.883 --> 53:42.453
but usually I gotta take it
that far for us to interact.

53:42.553 --> 53:44.088
You know? I look forward
to conversations.

53:44.188 --> 53:45.889
Even if it's something
small and minute,

53:45.989 --> 53:49.760
at least it gives me a chance to
trigger another conversation with him.

53:49.860 --> 53:51.462
I look forward to a few things.

53:51.562 --> 53:52.730
I look forward to December,

53:52.830 --> 53:55.099
because in December,
Frankie becomes very chatty.

53:55.199 --> 53:57.301
Otherwise, he's "One-word Kid."

53:57.401 --> 53:59.903
Parents, you know what I'm talking
about, kids, "One-word Kid"?

54:00.003 --> 54:02.072
And you try to talk to 'em.
"Hey, how was your day?" "Good."

54:02.172 --> 54:04.575
"You have any homework?" "Yeah."
"Are you going to do it?" "Maybe."

54:04.675 --> 54:05.743
"You hungry?" "Mmm-hmm"

54:05.843 --> 54:07.077
"What do you want?" "Food."

54:07.177 --> 54:08.447
(SCREAMS)

54:11.882 --> 54:13.959
Usually that's what I get.

54:14.084 --> 54:16.787
But December rolls around,
and guess what December is.

54:16.887 --> 54:18.756
December's when he
becomes very chatty,

54:18.856 --> 54:20.090
because he has an agenda.

54:20.190 --> 54:22.426
All of a sudden, he goes from
"One-word Kid" to very, like,

54:22.526 --> 54:24.495
"Hey, how's your week, Dad?
You doing good?

54:24.595 --> 54:26.530
"Yeah, how are the shows going?
You doing all right?

54:26.630 --> 54:28.165
"Do you need anything?
You need anything?"

54:28.265 --> 54:30.911
I'm like, "I needed this in July.
Just saying."

54:32.069 --> 54:34.805
And I know it's fake,
but at least, once again,

54:34.905 --> 54:38.208
it allows me to put my real
conversation on top of his fake one.

54:38.308 --> 54:40.351
And if that's what it takes,
then that's what it takes.

54:40.711 --> 54:44.114
In addition to that,
I look forward to problems.

54:44.214 --> 54:47.317
I like problems,
because if there's problems,

54:47.417 --> 54:50.387
Frankie and I can work on it
together to find a solution, right?

54:50.487 --> 54:53.258
And I see that as a
great form of bonding.

54:53.624 --> 54:55.025
Now don't get me wrong, you guys.

54:55.125 --> 54:57.271
Sometimes it's expensive.

54:58.495 --> 55:01.369
Yeah, you're laughing.
Let me tell you.

55:01.565 --> 55:03.901
Like, one time, they took
his iPhone from school,

55:04.001 --> 55:06.136
and he comes home,
and he's all devastated, right?

55:06.236 --> 55:08.472
He's like, "Dad, Dad,
I got to talk to you."

55:08.572 --> 55:09.973
I'm like, "What? Tell me. What?"

55:10.073 --> 55:11.375
(SOBBING) "They stole my phone."

55:11.475 --> 55:13.450
I'm like, "That's why
you're talking."

55:14.912 --> 55:16.647
And I started laughing.
He goes, "It's not funny."

55:16.747 --> 55:19.518
I go, "You have no
idea how funny it is."

55:20.083 --> 55:21.518
I go, "So what happened, Frankie?

55:21.618 --> 55:23.654
"So they broke into my locker at school,
and they took my iPhone,

55:23.754 --> 55:24.688
"they took my friend's iPhone,

55:24.788 --> 55:26.724
"and if we go to the school right now,
we can fill out a report.

55:26.824 --> 55:28.759
"We know exactly who did it.
Can we go to the school right now?"

55:28.859 --> 55:30.661
I go, "Listen, Frankie, I'd love to,

55:30.761 --> 55:32.429
"but I'm really tired.
I just got off a flight

55:32.529 --> 55:34.665
"and, you know,
I'm really, really tired.

55:34.765 --> 55:36.233
"I promise you tomorrow morning,
I'll take you early.

55:36.333 --> 55:38.335
"I'll help you fill out the
report and we'll turn it in."

55:38.435 --> 55:42.549
"Could we go right now?" I go, "Frankie,
seriously. Just please, tomorrow."

55:42.706 --> 55:44.608
(GROANS) "I need my phone."
I go, "Listen, Frankie,

55:44.708 --> 55:46.677
"you can handle one day
without your phone."

55:46.777 --> 55:49.613
He's not getting his way,
so he turns around,

55:49.713 --> 55:52.216
and he yells at
the ground, and he goes,

55:52.316 --> 55:54.052
"They took my phone!"

55:55.385 --> 55:57.521
I looked at him. I say,
"Hey, you took my freedom.

55:57.621 --> 55:59.266
"You don't hear me screaming."

56:00.224 --> 56:02.025
"I just accept it and process it,

56:02.125 --> 56:03.998
"and we move on. That's it."

56:05.462 --> 56:07.898
So then he asks,
"What's going to happen?"

56:07.998 --> 56:10.300
I go, "Well, I'm gonna go upstairs,
take a shower, and probably go to bed."

56:10.400 --> 56:12.936
"No, what's gonna happen if
I don't get my phone back?"

56:13.036 --> 56:15.072
I go, "That's a good question,
Frankie. I don't know."

56:15.172 --> 56:17.107
"You're not going to
get me a new one?"

56:17.207 --> 56:18.976
"No, dude. I already got you a phone.

56:19.076 --> 56:21.812
"It was your responsibility
to take care of that phone."

56:21.912 --> 56:24.815
"It's not fair." I go,
"Life's not fair, Frankie, okay?

56:24.915 --> 56:26.049
"But things happen."

56:26.149 --> 56:28.886
"You should get me a phone."
"Dude, seriously?"

56:28.986 --> 56:31.889
And then he looks at me, and he says,
and this kind of messed with me.

56:31.989 --> 56:33.724
He goes, "You should get me a phone.

56:33.824 --> 56:36.300
"It's nothing for you
to get me a new phone."

56:39.229 --> 56:43.468
"It's nothing for you
to get me a new phone."

56:43.834 --> 56:47.838
Bay Area, my son thinks
that what I do is easy.

56:47.938 --> 56:49.807
He thinks it's easy,
because all he sees

56:49.907 --> 56:51.675
when he attends one
or two shows per year

56:51.775 --> 56:54.978
is that I walk out onstage,
you guys start chanting,

56:55.078 --> 56:57.758
and then cool shit magically
appears in his room.

56:57.881 --> 56:59.253
(ALL LAUGHING)

57:01.885 --> 57:04.421
He doesn't realize that
this is actually a job

57:04.521 --> 57:06.256
and there's sacrifice
that comes along with it.

57:06.356 --> 57:09.259
So I told him. I said, "Listen,
Frankie, how 'bout this?

57:09.359 --> 57:14.198
"How 'bout you explain to me why
I should get you a new phone,

57:14.298 --> 57:17.741
"and if it makes sense,
I'll do it right now. Go."

57:18.035 --> 57:19.737
"I need one."

57:20.604 --> 57:23.874
I said, "No, Frankie. You're a teenager.
You don't need a phone.

57:23.974 --> 57:26.710
"A cell phone for a
teenager isn't a necessity.

57:26.810 --> 57:29.179
"It's a luxury, okay?

57:29.279 --> 57:33.325
"It's not a necessity,
it's a luxury."

57:33.717 --> 57:35.294
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

57:39.923 --> 57:42.793
He says, "What if
there's an emergency?"

57:42.893 --> 57:45.796
I go, "Like what?
Someone taking your phone?

57:45.896 --> 57:47.664
"What did you do today when
they took your phone?"

57:47.764 --> 57:51.001
"I went to the...
I went to the cafeteria,

57:51.101 --> 57:52.302
"and I talked to my friend Angel

57:52.402 --> 57:54.338
"and he let me use his phone,
and I called my mom."

57:54.438 --> 57:55.839
And I go, "And guess what?
If that doesn't work,

57:55.939 --> 57:57.474
"you can go to the office
and let them know,

57:57.574 --> 58:01.347
"'There's a family emergency,
please contact my mom or my dad.' Next."

58:01.578 --> 58:03.180
"What if you need to
get a hold of me?"

58:03.280 --> 58:05.824
"I know what school you go to."

58:06.116 --> 58:07.751
"What about when I'm walking home?"

58:07.851 --> 58:09.887
"I know the route that you take."

58:09.987 --> 58:12.823
And then he pulled this one out,
one of the greatest lines ever.

58:12.923 --> 58:16.570
"You know what?
You talk a lot about me on TV.

58:16.860 --> 58:19.131
"People know who I am now.

58:21.264 --> 58:23.637
"What if someone tries to kidnap me?"

58:26.303 --> 58:29.143
I said, "You weigh 225. Good luck.

58:31.641 --> 58:33.110
"They are not kidnapping your ass

58:33.210 --> 58:34.878
"without an iPhone
and a box of Oreos.

58:34.978 --> 58:38.048
"That's the only way
that's going to happen."

